post_text:
FOOD SERVICE GROCERY PICK UP INFORMATION

HSD grocery food pick up is starting this week August 27th and will be every Thursday there after until notified. It will be at the Highland Junior High Parking lot from 11:00 am to 4:00 pm. Student does not have to be present.

During the first pick up, the staff will check in the parent and give them student ID cards. Parent needs to bring the ID cards each time they pick up food. There is only one pick up per family.

Students food eligibility applies. For example, if you are a full paying student you will be billed for meals. Parents need to fill out the lunch application by September 30. Students eligibility carries over from last year for the first 30 days of school.

Highland High School has an exciting opportunity to offer computer science next year. We are investing in our students by partnering with Microsoft Philanthropies TEALS to offer Introduction to Computer Science.
As a TEALS partner school, Highland High School needs technical volunteers to team-teach these this course with our teacher. We will hold the course first period, allowing volunteers to go to work after volunteering. If you work in tech and would be interested in making a difference in our students‚Äô future success, please contact me by calling (509) 678-8805, via email at bjensen@highland.wednet.edu or apply at Microsoft.com/TEALS.
Please share this with technical industry professionals in your network. You can read more about the TEALS Program on their website at Microsoft.com/TEALS.

Attention Highland Junior High Students!
We are going to have a difficult time filling the pages of our yearbook when we aren't at school, so we need your help!
Please send pictures of the ways you're spending your time during the closure. Are you learning a new skill? Like sewing or building things? Learning how to bake a cake? Have you been playing board games with your family? Group video chats with friends? Are you doing workouts? Exercising in the yard to stay in shape?
Send any and all pictures to Mrs. Matson and we will get started on this NEW section to document this part of our year!

Also, don't forget to go vote for the Student Choice Awards! Most of the 7th grade has done this, but 8th grade definietly needs to! Links are on the JH webpage...email Mrs. Matson if you have any questions :)
Thanks and stay safe and healthy!

Here are the general steps to setup Highland email accounts on a user‚Äôs phone.

In the Email program go to Add New Account. (May be worded different depending on the email program and phone.)
Make sure to choose Exchange as the type.
Enter your full district email address (Example: BrianJ27@highland.wednet.edu)
Use your computer login password as the password
When prompted accept the Use Agreement.
Decide how you want to Sync your info.

Students can also go to Office.com and login.

Updated: Highland School District Child Nutrition Plan 03/16/2020
COVID-19 Emergency School Closure
March 23-April 24, 2020

WHO: All children ages 0 to 18 in the Highland School District area (Cowiche & Tieton)
Children must be present to receive meal

Where: TIS (Tieton Intermediate School) front entrance walk up style.
Highland Junior High (Student Services Office) entrance walk up style. Child Nutrition staff will serve them.

When: Meals to be served Monday, 3/23, 2020 thru Friday, 4/24/2020, between 10:30 am to 12 pm to avoid large gatherings
Not available week of April 6 thru the 10th

How: Each student will receive 1 lunch meal for the day of and 1 cold breakfast for the next morning.

Lunch Meal: May Include hot finger foods, cold sandwiches, or shelf stable entrees & cheese stick, whole fruit/re-packaged fruit, pre-packaged vegetables, & milk.

Breakfast Meal: May include Muffin, cereal bar, cereal, honey buns, donut - each meal will come with a fruit or juice & milk

post_text:
The Highland School District, along with other SCAC league school districts, will be postponing all school-sponsored student events effective immediately through April 12, 2020 at which time we will re-evaluate the situation. This decision also suspends all student events hosted by Highland schools where outside participants would be traveling into the community. This includes activities such as home and away athletic contests, student field trips outside of our community, concerts, and other program related events.

Please keep in mind that the health and safety of our students, staff, and community is our priority when making such decisions.

Information regarding rescheduling of events will be made available when conditions improve and/or are recommended by health experts.

Please check the Highland School District Website for more information.

post_text: The MWC students participated in an activity called ‚ÄúPeer Pulse‚Äù. They passed the ‚Äúpulse‚Äù or a squeeze around the circle in a quick fashion. During the activity, students needed to use learning skills like focusing, teamwork, and using a quiet voice in order to successfully complete the task! The activity was an introduction into the lesson about negative peer pressure. Students learned how to be assertive in order to resist peer pressure, used problem solving skills, and practiced saying no in sample scenarios.

post_text: It is with deep regret that the Highland School District must share that one of our beloved community members and district employees passed away unexpectedly today due to an accident involving a district school bus and district vehicle. Students on the bus were not injured but Rosa Gutierrez, a seven year Highland employee and lifetime resident, passed away. Rosa worked in the kitchen and at Marcus Whitman Cowiche Elementary School where she enjoyed interacting with the staff and students. She always had a smile and cared for everyone around her. Rosa was an amazing person with a huge heart and was dearly loved by all. We are in shock and are heartsick. Our thoughts and prayers are with the family.

post_text: We are hosting a ‚ÄúCelebrate Tieton Night‚Äù at 6:30pm on January 18th. We will present the special state award Tieton Intermediate School earned and unveil that award banner at the beginning of this celebration. The 5th and 6th grade bands will perform along with a 4th grade performance. We will also have an art show in the cafeteria. Additionally, our students will present information about growth mindset and our Positive Behavior Intervention Program (PBIS). All students will have a role to play that evening. If your student will not be attending, please send a note or call your child‚Äôs teacher as soon as possible so that he/she is not assigned a role in presenting that evening.
